# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered-plants-of-europe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] It was first published and described in Willdenowia Vol.23 on page 157 in 1993.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The species is a semi-woody herbaceous plant with drooping shoots, which can be up to 60 centimeters long.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The alternate leaves are compound and are divided either once or twice.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The greyish-green leaflets are linear or spear-shaped, between 1 and 5 millimeters wide, and covered with white matted hair.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The small purple-mauve flowers are densely grouped in terminal flower heads that resemble large solitary flowers.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The outer flowers bear a single large petal, while the inner flowers are tubular.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The achenes looks like the seeds of wheat and have a lot of fine hair.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The Akamas centaurea is endemic to Cyprus, where it is found in three localities on the Akamas Peninsula in western Cyprus.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The three localities are the Avakas, Koufon, and Falkonias gorges.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] Its total range measures around seven square kilometres, of which less than one square kilometre is inhabited by the plant.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The species inhabits steep, shaded, humid limestone cliffs that have other vegetation growing in the crevices. it is found at elevations of 70–150 m.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The Akamas centaurea has a very long flowering and fruiting period.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The bloom period is between the months of May and November.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The fruiting period is between the months of July to December.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The Akamas centaurea is listed as being critically endangered on the IUCN Red List due to its small range and population, as well as declining habitat quality in its range.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] Surveys of the species in 2005 and 2009 estimated the population to number 550 and 590 individuals respectively.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] Following the discovery of a new subpopulation in 2012, a 2013 study increased the population estimate to around 800 plants.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] Illegal grazing by goats poses a severe threat to the Akamas centaurea, leading to erosion and trampling of plants.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] However, this is only a threat to a small part of the species' overall population which is accessible to goats.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] Another threat is soil erosion due to landslides and rockfalls, a problem the species is vulnerable due to the geological features of the gorges it grows in.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The species is protected under Appendix I of the Berne Convention and Annexes II and IV of the Habitats Directive.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] It is also recognised as an endangered species in Cyprus.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The Akamas Peninsula is a protected area under the Natura 2000 program and Avakas Gorge, which hosts the largest subpopulation of the species, is a Natural Micro-Reserve under Cypriot law.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] The Akamas centaurea is also a subject of ex-situ conservation measures, having been grown at the Cyprus Agricultural Research Institute and the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/akamas-centaury] CARI and other universities also store seeds of the plant at their seed banks.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/apium-bermejoi] Formerly included in the genus *Apium*, genetic analysis showed it not to be closely related to the type species of that genus (wild celery *Apium graveolens*), and it has now been transferred to the genus *Helosciadium* in the tribe Oenantheae.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/apium-bermejoi] Its natural habitat is Mediterranean-type shrubby vegetation, known as matorral.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/apium-bermejoi] It was classified as 'critically endangered' in the IUCN Red List in 2006.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/apium-bermejoi] In the European Union it has been designated as a 'priority species' under Annex II of the Habitats Directive since 1992, which means areas in which it occurs can be declared Special Areas of Conservation, *if* these areas belong to one of the number of habitats listed in Annex I of the directive.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-barbaricina] The species forms a monophyletic clade with the other columbine species endemic to Corsica and Sardinia, *Aquilegia bernardii*, *Aquilegia litardierei*, *Aquilegia nugorensis* and *Aquilegia nuragica*.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-barbaricina] The specific name *barbaricina* refers to the Barbagia region of eastern Sardinia, where the species is found.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-barbaricina] The species is almost extinct due to habitat loss and unsustainable collecting.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-barbaricina] It is an IUCN Red List Critically Endangered plant species and IUCN Top 50 Campaign Mediterranean Island Plant.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] The species forms a monophyletic clade with the other columbine species endemic to Corsica and Sardinia, *Aquilegia barbaricina*, *Aquilegia bernardii*, *Aquilegia litardierei*, and *Aquilegia nugorensis*.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] However, it is clearly genetically isolated from the other Sardinian species.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] The specific epithet *nuragica* means "Nuragic" in Latin and Italian, referring to the Nuragic civilization that flourished on Sardinia in the Bronze Age.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] The decline in the plant's population seems to be due to natural factors.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] However, due to the inaccessibility of the site, it is difficult to research the decline.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] It is not affected by grazing due to the plant's toxicity.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] The species is currently not under any legal protection.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] Despite occurring within the Gennargentu National Park, the lack of a management committee means no effective preservation measures are in place.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/aquilegia-nuragica] The natural habitat of *Aquilegia nuragica* is in Mediterranean shrubby vegetation.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/endangered-plants-of-europe] Propragation has been conducted using in vitro techniques in facilities across the country.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/endangered-plants-of-europe] This method of conservation is used in parts of the world to preserve plants for as long as possible.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/endangered-plants-of-europe] In vitro propagation has allowed material to be kept in in vitro gene banks, and this will expand with deeper developments in cryopreservation technology.
[src:endangered-plants-of-europe/endangered-plants-of-europe] An increasing number of botanic gardens now have in vitro facilities, and information on techniques is distributed between these in addition to cultures.
